				<li id="16492531" class="cmnt-root" data="69" data-d="1646993470000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t578924/Lusat's-Glintstone-Staff" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">11 Mar 2022 05:11</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16492531" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">I just took a look at the game files as I could not find confirmation of if this staff is bugged or not.<br/>Lusat&apos;s Glintstone Staff: Item ID 33240000 has a passive effect listed as ID 1934<br/>When checking what effect 1934 is, it looks to be a self buff that increases the cost of Sorceries with a multiplier of 1.5 (Default being 1.0) so +50% cost in casts. And that is all the effect has listed. Generally for multi effects like this one of 3 scenarios happen.<br/>1. All the effects are listed under the same SpEffect ID, this does not seem to be the case with this.<br/>2. First effect is listed on that SpEffect and the subsequent effects are cycled by it. Essentially one effect chain activates the rest, this is not the case either since 1934 not have any other effect referenced to be being cycled with it.<br/>3. Weapons and Armor have 3 passive effects they can have attributed to them directly. For this staff only one effect is listed, and that is 1934 as mentioned before.<br/><br/>My conclusion from looking at this would be that they accidentally missed adding the damage buff effect. I would consider that the description is busted, but it increasing costs by 50% without any other benefit sounds odd.<br/><br/>The other option I can think of is that its base scaling is so high that it accounts as an increase in damage. From my experience making mods for past games, I think this would be the easiest way to ensure you raise the damage of all spells which seems to be the goal of this staff. However, I am not personally sure how to assess the math on that so I will list the scaling as I see them and hopefully someone can make sense of them. Including their IDs in case someone wants to look into this as well.<br/>Name: ID: INT Scaling | FTH Scaling<br/>Glintstone Staff: 33000000: 85 | 0<br/>Crystal Staff: 3304000: 94 | 0<br/>Gelmir Glintstone Staff: 33050000: 40 | 40<br/>Demi-Human Queen&apos;s Staff: 33060000: 75 | 0<br/>Carian Regal Scepter: 33090000: 96 | 0<br/>Digger&apos;s Staff: 33120000: 76 | 0<br/>Astrologer&apos;s Staff: 33130000: 89 | 0<br/>Carian Glintblade Staff: 33170000: 88 | 0<br/>Prince of Death&apos;s Staff: 33180000: 58 | 58<br/>Albinauric Staff: 33190000: 30 | 0<br/>Academy Glintstone Staff: 33200000: 91 | 0 <br/>Carian Glintstone Staff: 33210000: 85 | 0<br/>Azur&apos;s Glintstone Staff: 33230000: 92 | 0<br/>Lusat&apos;s Glintstone Staff: 33240000: 110 | 0<br/>Meteorite Staff: 33250000: 192 | 0<br/>Staff of the Guilty: 33260000: 0 | 76<br/>Rotten Crystal Staff: 33270000: 93 | 0<br/>Staff of Loss: 33280000: 84 | 0</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16492531" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16492531" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">5</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>72</p><i class="add">+1</i></section><section class="t-down"><span></span><p>3</p><i class="sub">-1</i></section></div><